1.m_mText: "Here, one may witness the dance of the stars and the unbroken wheel of fate."

1002.m_mText: "The approaching footsteps disrupted the silence, drawing the attention of the pensive youth. At last, he lifted his head from deep contemplation."

1004.m_mText: "Three figures arrived, their presence at odds with any fascination for the stars above."

1005.m_mText: "'If you can be here, why can't we?!'"

1006.m_mText: "'We came to observe the moon,' Aiona explained gently."

1008.m_mText: "'Didn't take you lot for the moon-gazing type...'"

1009.m_mText: "Arms crossed, Empousa huffed dramatically. 'Well, if you must know, it's because Aiona found some old journal in the library.'"

1011.m_mText: "'It contains lunar observation records. The author claimed it was the culmination of years of research.'"

1012.m_mText: "'All the observations were made here, so we figured there might be missing pages left behind.'"

1013.m_mText: "'If you're interested, Noah, why not help us search?'"

1014.m_mText: "The long-buried history left behind by those before had finally found its chance to see the light of day."

1015.m_mText: "Amid the quiet of the observatory, the sounds of a 'treasure hunt' echoed in every corner."

1016.m_mText: "'Is this… the moon?' Aiona held up a page from the journal, showing a page of black scribbles."

1017.m_mText: "'This? Seriously? That's hideous!' Empousa gave a look of disgust."

1018.m_mText: "'Isn't that just a bunch of potholes? Doesn't look like the moon to me.'"

1020.m_mText: "'And shouldn't the moon be like the sun—a glowing sphere of light? This just looks like a dark, lifeless plane.'"

1021.m_mText: "'Exactly! If the moon is this dark, how do you explain the moonlight?' Jestel furrowed her brow in confusion."

1022.m_mText: "'There must be more pages. If we keep searching, we might find an explanation for why the moon looks like this.'"

1024.m_mText: "Before long, they stumbled upon a new discovery."

1025.m_mText: "'Got something! This looks like the last record—let me take a look…'"

1026.m_mText: "The group gathered around Empousa, eyes fixed on the page in her hands."

1027.m_mText: "It was a densely packed entry, meticulously charting the moon's shifting phases over the course of a year."

1028.m_mText: "'It says here these are lunar phase records, with sketches of the moon's appearance and corresponding dates.'"

1029.m_mText: "'"March twenty-ninth, new moon—The moon is not visible today." The sketch is just a completely empty sky.'"

1030.m_mText: "'"April fifth, first quarter—Only the western side of the moon is illuminated today." So this is called a first quarter moon? I always thought it was just a half-moon.'"

1031.m_mText: "'"April twelfth, full moon—At last, the moon reveals its full form today." And here's the sketch of the complete moon.'"

1032.m_mText: "'Truly astounding… For an entire year, at the same time each day, they came here to record the moon's appearance.'"

1033.m_mText: "'Even among the Alita family, such meticulous documentation is rare,' Aiona remarked in admiration."

1035.m_mText: "'Though this one doesn't look like another lunar phase record.' Noah carefully took the final page in hand."

1036.m_mText: "'Look—there's a note from the author: "After more than three years, I've finally brought this preliminary star-gazing journal to a close."'"

1037.m_mText: "'"This is a calculated and theorized trajectory of the moon's movement. It may not be entirely precise, but I shall continue refining it."'"

1038.m_mText: "'"If I no longer walk this world, may my research live on, passed down through the ages. Someone will carry this torch."'"

2001001.m_mText: "'I'm not all that interested… I'd rather explore at my own pace.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'Not a chance. You're coming with us—that's an order!'"

2001003.m_mText: "Noah let out a quiet sigh. 'Very well… my lady.'"

2002001.m_mText: "A rare flicker of curiosity stirred within him. 'All right, I'll come along. I'm a little curious myself—what does the moon truly look like?'"

2002002.m_mText: "'After all… it's the home we're meant to return to someday.'"

2003001.m_mText: "'Are you truly prepared? What if the moon turns out to be nothing like we imagined?'"

2003002.m_mText: "'The moon doesn't owe it to us to match our imagination.'"

2003003.m_mText: "'And besides, it's still home. Don't tell me you're getting cold feet now!'"

1.m_mText: "'We didn't even catch a glimpse of the moon's surface today!'"

1002.m_mText: "'Our luck's been awful. How many nights has it been now?'"

1003.m_mText: "'It's a shame I still haven't deciphered the formulas from that last set of notes…' Aiona sounded slightly frustrated."

1004.m_mText: "'If I could crack them, we wouldn't have to rely on luck anymore.'"

1006.m_mText: "'Even you, heir to the Alita family, have no clue?'"

1007.m_mText: "'Aiona's studied astronomy since she was a child. When it comes to stargazing, few can match her.'"

1008.m_mText: "'But the journal's author… seems even more versed in celestial lore than she is.'"

1009.m_mText: "'In all the long history of the Alita family, I've never heard of an astronomer who could map the surface of the moon.'"

1010.m_mText: "'The observations we found in that journal… the level of insight was something not seen in a hundred years.'"

1011.m_mText: "'Why haven't I heard of them before…?' A rare expression of doubt crossed her face."

1012.m_mText: "'Come on, don't dwell on it too much, Aiona.'"

1013.m_mText: "'I have to uncover the history behind that journal.' She lifted her gaze to the sky."

1014.m_mText: "'Forgive me, but I must go for now. I'll uncover the story behind it.'"

1015.m_mText: "The stars shifted, time passed, and still, Aiona's research showed little progress."

1016.m_mText: "Dragging Noah behind her, Empousa stepped into Aiona's room with concern. 'Aiona, how's the research coming along?'"

1017.m_mText: "Aiona let out a troubled sigh. 'There's been no real progress.'"

1018.m_mText: "'Why don't we take a look together? We might spot something you missed.'"

1020.m_mText: "'Let's see… You've gathered quite the stack of notes.'"

1021.m_mText: "For a moment, the room was silent, broken only by the rustle of turning pages."

1022.m_mText: "Then, the quiet was shattered by Empousa's sudden cry of excitement."

1023.m_mText: "'Look at this! This little map—doesn't it look like Eye of God?' She held up a page with barely contained glee."

1024.m_mText: "Noah shook his head. 'Not seeing it at all.'"

1025.m_mText: "'Come on! Eye of God belongs to the Bathory family—I'd know it anywhere.'"

1026.m_mText: "'The rest of the journal must be hidden there. Let's go!'"

1027.m_mText: "Without another word, Empousa dragged the other two out the door and made straight for Eye of God."

1028.m_mText: "'This is it. Let me see… According to the notes, it should be buried beneath three stones.'"

1029.m_mText: "'Could it be that one?' Noah pointed toward a cluster of three stones in the distance."

1031.m_mText: "The three of them began digging with eager hands. Not far beneath the surface, they unearthed a stone box."

1032.m_mText: "Brushing the dust from its lid, Aiona opened the box with care and examined the pages within."

1033.m_mText: "'We've found it. This one… it reads like a personal account.' She cradled the yellowed pages gently in her hands."

1034.m_mText: "As a sister of the Church, I was meant to devote my days and nights to the praise of our great lord, Aeon."

1035.m_mText: "And yet, I found myself drawn instead to the shifting path of the moon, to the hidden patterns among the stars."

1036.m_mText: "So I gave myself wholly to the study of the moon."

1037.m_mText: "To my astonishment, I discovered that all we had been taught about it… was wrong."

1038.m_mText: "I cannot say whether what I've done is right or wrong. After all, someone like me was never permitted to pursue knowledge on her own."

1039.m_mText: "But even if my actions have already strayed beyond the bounds of doctrine, I still wish to continue this research."

1040.m_mText: "'A Bathory nun? That must've been ages ago… back when the Bathory lands still belonged to the High Priest.'"

1041.m_mText: "'In that era, no matter her status—noble or clergy—a woman would never have been permitted to conduct such research.'"

1042.m_mText: "'Which is likely why she hid her notes in so many places… She couldn't risk being discovered, but she also couldn't bring herself to abandon the study of the stars.'"

1043.m_mText: "'Still, this journal seems incomplete. Some pages must have scattered…'"

1045.m_mText: "'I wonder where the last of the pages could be…'"

1046.m_mText: "'Looks like I'll have to do it. No one's better at treasure hunts than me.'"

2001001.m_mText: "Noah offered a quiet comfort. 'Not every scholar's work is given the chance to be passed on.'"

2002001.m_mText: "'What's the point in dwelling on it? What's done is done—better to think about what comes next.'"

1.m_mText: "琪安德marches on, once again the day has come for the Bathory Elder Council's monthly assembly. Today's theme is—irth._"

1002.m_mText: "'The 1,861st Grand Assembly for introspection and review regarding matters of glory, faith, power, and fidelity, and the centennial outlook for the Bathory family's Moon Ascension Initiative.'"

1003.m_mText: "Firstly, let us welcome the elder presiding over our assembly on the east side—the most venerable of the Bathory family, whose chilling armor strikes terror into the hearts of all who hear his name—Baphomet the Soulless!"

1004.m_mText: "A feeble light sputtered to life beside the loftiest seat on the eastern side of the Hall of Honor. Baphomet—despite his eyeless visage—squinted to adjust to the faint illumination, then brought his massive axe crashing down upon the ground..."

1005.m_mText: "A deep, hoarse sound emanated from Baphomet's armor as it shifted: 'To think that I, in my twilight years, should find myself reduced to such a state. I, who was once feared throughout the realm as the 'Soulless'—"

1006.m_mText: "Hold on a second... It's a bit late to be asking this, but why is he called the Soulless? Wasn't this character supposed to be a soul that lost his physical body and is now attached to armor?"

1007.m_mText: "If he truly is just an empty shell without a soul... how does he differ from the shattered, stained piles of armor strewn across any battlefield? Can we still view 'him' as an existence? And perhaps more importantly—"

1008.m_mText: "Lost in thought, Baphomet slowly turned his massive, rusted helmet. At the edge of his vision, barely discernible in the darkness, stood a time-worn trophy."

1009.m_mText: "A muffled voice reverberated from within the armor: 'In that distant year, I was but a humble retainer in service to the Matriarch.'"

1010.m_mText: "His sincere recollection had a fatal allure that required neither the eloquent spin of a bard nor the stirring melody of a minstrel."

1012.m_mText: "'Hey old man, they say when someone starts dwelling on the past, it means they've already got one foot in the grave.' A grating voice suddenly cut through the shadow, rudely interrupting Baphomet."

1013.m_mText: "...Let is introduce the attendee sitting to the south, the one who forsook his entire past to join the Bathory family... Esteemed guests, please welcome the youngest of the Bathory Elders—Gilrain Cidhall!"

1014.m_mText: "Baphomet remained unperturbed by Gilrain's intrusion. His gaze, unwavering and fixed upon the trophy, betrayed no reaction—as though he were already lost in the mists of memory. 'At the very least,' he intoned solemnly, 'I still possess recollections worthy of sharing.'"

1015.m_mText: "The cruel words hung in the air, as if freezing the very atmosphere... This verbal assault landed with nothing short of a fatal blow!"

1016.m_mText: "As expected of the man known as the 'Soulless'—his words are lack any warmth."

1017.m_mText: "The absence of memories is one of Gilrain's deepest sorrows. Whether due to an unspeakable secret or a necessary sacrifice, he has lost all recollection of his former human life."

1018.m_mText: "The Cidhall family, once intimately familiar to him, now fails to stir even the faintest emotion in Gilrain's heart."

1019.m_mText: "By the way, among Gilrain's other woes is... the disdain of the Bathory tailors. His tendency to destroy shirts in Battle has forced him to spend most of his time bare-chested."

1020.m_mText: "'Are you sure those memories are really your own, old-timer? Because you...' Gilrain paused, deliberately scanning the cumbersome armor from top to bottom."

1021.m_mText: "'...probably don't even know who your previous body belonged to, do you?' As he spoke, a sardonic smile played across Gilrain's lips."

1022.m_mText: "'Cidhall, my years are as timeless as the rust upon this armor...' Baphomet responded, unmoved by Gilrain's provocation. His expression remained as impassive as his ancient armor."

1023.m_mText: "'I have weathered desolation, and been graced with the sight of the crimson moon looming over the world. Thus... none yearn more fervently than I to reclaim the days of yore, to reforge our lost glory!'"

1024.m_mText: "'What is it that you really want to reforge? The glory of the Bathory family... or that worn-out vessel of yours...?'"

1025.m_mText: "Gilrain stared at Baphomet with a half-smile. Those eyes seemed to pierce through the ancient armor, probing the secrets hidden within."

1026.m_mText: "Baphomet paused, then snapped his gaze from the trophy to Gilrain. 'Gilrain Cidhall... Ha Ha Hahahaha!'"

1027.m_mText: "As his laugh erupted like thunder, he swung his axe to point at Gilrain. 'I see now... your true objective in joining the Bathory family was me all along!'"

1028.m_mText: "'You Cidhall brat! Come clean with your schemes, and I might just let you walk away with your bones intact!'"

1029.m_mText: "The atmosphere suddenly grew tense. Gilrain's long hair stirred as if by an unseen force, while Baphomet tightened his grip on his axe, his gauntlet creaking ominously. It seemed a great battle was imminent..."

1030.m_mText: "'Knock, knock! Is anyone here?' A clear, youthful voice rang out at the entrance of the hall. 'Oh, Morain and the old-timer are already here...'"

1031.m_mText: "The girl casually strolled to the seat to the north and gracefully sat down. Only then did she lazily glance at the two figures about to unleash hell. 'I thought I'd the first one here...'"

1032.m_mText: "'Oh... don't mind me. I'll be busy selling my finest healing potions to both sides in the heat of the battle!'"

1033.m_mText: "As she spoke, the girl tilted her head and raised her four snall fists in a cheering gesture—yes, you read that right, 'four' fists. As for why she has four fists..."

1034.m_mText: "—Let us warmly welcome our attendee seated to the north, the young lady who purchased her elder position for an exorbitant sum, founder and president of the Puppet Association—Bella Slade!"

1035.m_mText: "Note: At the Puppet Association's request, we include their promotional list for discounted items. The list reads: 'Our store's motto is: If a wealthy customer and a Bell Ringer fall into the river at the same time—'"

1036.m_mText: "...Hmm, looks like the second half of that sentence is on some other promotional material."

1037.m_mText: "'...Tch, if we start fighting in front of this con artist, who knows when we'll be forced to buy things we'd never need,' Gilrain grumbled, his brows furrowed."

1038.m_mText: "Before the words had even finished, Gilrain had already melted into the shadow, materializing in the seat to the south. He stared blankly into the nothingness, utterly bored."

1039.m_mText: "Baphomet lowered his axe while looking down at Gilrain with disdain. 'Hmph. Next time you dare provoke me, boy, you'd best measure your own abilities first.'"

1040.m_mText: "'—Especially financial strength.' At this moment, Baphomet's posture was exceptionally straight, for he was the Puppet Association's biggest suc—ahem, most esteemed patron."

1041.m_mText: "'Goodness, why did you two stop? Just pretend I'm not here! Whether it's weapons or medicine, or even items you can't find on the open market...'"

1042.m_mText: "'For the right price... me and my Puppet Association will be your most loyal ally. Isn't that right, Jacintha?'"

1043.m_mText: "As Bella spoke, she gently stroked a black cat that has suddenly appeared in her arms. The cat settled contently on her lap, occasionally letting out soft, joyful purrs."

1044.m_mText: "'Achoo!' Caught off guard by a sudden sneeze, Gilrain gives Bella an annoyed look."

2001001.m_mText: "Can he truly revive the Bathory family with such a 'body'?"

2002001.m_mText: "Can life be defined by something other than 'body' and 'soul'?"

2003001.m_mText: "Know that this is now his character design was ruined!"

1.m_mText: "'Now that all are present, I, Baphomet, hereby declare the commencement of the monthly Bathory Elder Council Grand Assembly—'"

1002.m_mText: "The full title being: 'The 1,862nd Grand Assembly for introspection and review regarding matters of glory, faith, power, and fidelity, and the centennial outlook for the Bathory family's Moon Ascension Initiative—'"

1004.m_mText: "'The purpose of this assembly, newly appointed elders, is to showcase how we transform glory into tangible symbols that inspire our younger members. But I ask you this: in recent years, how many new trophies and medals have actually been added to our collection?'"

1005.m_mText: "Baphomet adopts the bearing of a seasoned Grand Elder, imparting wisdom to his juniors with paternal gravitas."

1006.m_mText: "'A-Achoo!' Instead of a dignified response, Gilrain's ill-timed sneeze shatters the solemn atmosphere. His worsening cat allergy, it seems, has chosen a most inopportune moment to manifest."

1007.m_mText: "'Hey Gilrain, looks like you're not feeling too well. But I've got just the thing—the latest product from the Puppet Association!'"

1008.m_mText: "As she spoke, Bella reached into her briefcase and produced a vial of clear liquid and gave it a shake in Gilrain's direction."

1009.m_mText: "'How thoughtful of you,' Gilrain said without any emotion."

1010.m_mText: "'Ever since I became an elder and you pushed that so-called memory-restoring medicine on me...' Gilrain trailed off, as if recalling something deeply uncomfortable. He fell silent for a moment."

1011.m_mText: "'Wait a second! Don't tell me Gilrain didn't bother to read the fine print on the bottom of the bottle? The warnings are clearly stated right there—'"

1012.m_mText: "Bella rattled off this line with practiced ease, blurring the line between a well-rehearsed sales pitch and the automated response of a puppet."

1013.m_mText: "'That potion...' Gilrain seemed to be restraining himself. 'It wasn't even clear! How was I supposed to—' He suddenly exploded, 'You can't see the bottom until you've drunk it all!' His eyes blazed with such fury they could have set the room ablaze."

1014.m_mText: "'Meow...?' As if awakened by Gilrain, the black cat leapt down from its usual spot and began pacing around the room."

1015.m_mText: "Until it spotted a rusted trophy and trotted over. Like a lion toying with its prey, the cat curiously batted at the trophy with its paws."

1016.m_mText: "As the trophy rolled back and forth between the cat's paws, Baphomet considered intervening, but was unwilling to lower himself to do so—"

1017.m_mText: "He may be one of the four great elders, but it was just a cat after all! For the Grand Elder to be frolicking with a cat during a meeting—how undignified!"

1018.m_mText: "The observant Gilrain noticed some rust being rubbed off the trophy by the black cat's paws and couldn't help but mock Bella, 'Looks like that rust remover you sold the old man was less effective than a pair of cat paws.'"

1019.m_mText: "Bella, completely unfazed after being exposed, replied, 'Well, those are Jacintha's little paws after all. What can I say? Jacintha is the cutest cat in the world!'"

1020.m_mText: "'Baphomet, didn't you say this was the place where honor can be realized'? Sincerity and keeping one's word are part of honor, aren't they? How do you expect to restore our glory with this crooked merchant around?'"

1021.m_mText: "Baphomet gazed contemplatively at the trophy on the ground... As the rust gradually peeled away, it revealed a tarnished surface—far from the brilliant, gold sheen he had once imagined."

1023.m_mText: "He had always considered himself the pillar of the Bathory family. Now, with the family's prestige and power at its lowest, it was his inescapable duty to rise to the occasion and revive the their former glory."

1024.m_mText: "Having reached a momentous decision, a reverberating clang rang out as Baphomet slammed his axe onto the ground. In that instant, Baphomet's silhouette towered, grand and imposing."

1025.m_mText: "The other three elders snapped their attention to Baphomet—now the most venerable and influential figure within the family. He gazed across the gathering, then slowly began to speak—"

1026.m_mText: "A deathly hush descended upon the scene, each person ruminating on Baphomet's words. Even the black cat quietly padded back to its seat, its eyes blinking with an expression that seemed to teeter between comprehension and bewilderment..."

1027.m_mText: "It wasn't until Bella solemnly interjected that everyone was jolted back to the reality: 'Well... while I couldn't quite grasp everything that was said, it seems the old-timer is suggesting that today's meeting has come to an end.'"

1028.m_mText: "'Ah, I still have to take inventory of the new merchandise. So much to do!' Bella murmured to herself as she opened her small briefcase to inspect the goods—one could only imagine just how many things that case held."

1029.m_mText: "'Hm... she's probably right. After all, he is her most valued customer. Who else would know him better?' Gilrain, unexpectedly in agreement with Bella, remarked as he dissolved into the shadows."

2001001.m_mText: "Gilrain glanced around. 'Why aren't we meeting in the usual place?'"

2001002.m_mText: "'I'm pleased you've noticed such details. It shows you hold our past meetings in high regard.'"

2001003.m_mText: "Though his expression was undiscernable—for he had none—Baphomet's joy was evident from the tone of his words."

2001004.m_mText: "'...Uh, the last meeting was outdoors. That's kind of hard to miss—anyone with eyes would remember'—but eyes was precisely something Baphomet did not have."

2002001.m_mText: "Bella opened her briefcase. 'What's the topic for this meeting?'"

2002002.m_mText: "'It gladdens me to hear your curious question, for it shows the duty of an elder has taken root in your heart.'"

2002003.m_mText: "Though his expression was undiscernable—for he had none—Baphomet's joy was evident from the tone of his words."

2002004.m_mText: "'What are you yapping about, old-timer? I just wanted to use this opportunity to do a big sale for all the stuff I've been hoarding!'"

2003001.m_mText: "Huh? It jumped from the 1,861 to 1,862...? Wait, who the hell is actually reading the ludicrously long meeting names?"

2003002.m_mText: "...Uh, err, that was a hallucination. What's done is done, so—What? No, no, no, I wasn't getting mad that this tiny oversight was pointed out! That's just silly!"

2003003.m_mText: "This tale is narrated by (one of) the most esteemed bards on Minexus. It's impossible for such a silly mistake to occur. Right, it would never occur, 'til the end of time."

2004001.m_mText: "'True honor needs no physical record. It's etched indelibly in the hearts of all.' Baphomet's weathered voice echoed through the Hall of Honor, resonating within every soul present."

2005001.m_mText: "Though our Matriarch is sealed away, the Bathory family endures. As long as we elders pass down the Bathory spirit, our lineage shall persist! Our resurgence is on the horizon!'"

2005002.m_mText: "Baphomet's enthusiastic declaration rang out in the Hall of Honor, touching everyone present."

2006001.m_mText: "'The Bathory family needs more skilled blacksmiths to craft trophies!' Baphomet's enthusiastic declaration rang out in the Hall of Honor, touching everyone present."

1.m_mText: "Blood is an irreplaceable essence in this world. To study blood is to delve into the very nature of power itself."

1002.m_mText: "'Why do we keep changing the location of the Elder meeting?' Gilrain grumbled before the meeting even began. 'What's wrong with the old location? Getting bored?'"

1003.m_mText: "'Naturally, we hold our meetings in locations that reflect the subject matter,' Baphomet patiently explained to the newcomer. 'This has been our custom since long before you joined the Bathory family.'"

1004.m_mText: "Even if he did almost become a Bell Ringer. Even if he is a direct Cidhall descendant. So what? In the vast river of time, I have seen far too many such 'prodigies' come and go."

1005.m_mText: "Just then, with a meow, the black cat—predictably the last elder to arrive—leapt onto its seat and promptly dozed off."

1006.m_mText: "'Let us commence our monthly Elder meeting,' Baphomet, in his capacity as Chief Elder, declared. 'Our agenda today concerns the recent Blood conflicts among other families.'"

1007.m_mText: "'What business is it of ours, and what blood conflicts do other families get into?' Gilrain scoffed. 'Do we even have the power to stick our noses in?'"

1008.m_mText: "'Are we going to supply them with materials for war?' the Bella inquired. No doubt the Puppet Association was already turning a tidy profit from the War raging across the continent."

1009.m_mText: "'No. I'm referring to the true power that the major families have demonstrated during this series of conflicts. Bella, you should have the most insight into this matter.'"

1010.m_mText: "'I can tell you right away which family spent the most money!' Bella felt the conversation had shifted to her area of expertise."

1011.m_mText: "'Money is indeed a form of power, but...' Baphomet attempted to guide the conversation in a different direction."

1012.m_mText: "'It's the 'Bull'... the Cidhall family!' Bella exclaimed eagerly, turning to Gilrain. 'As expected of Elder Gilrain's family!'"

1013.m_mText: "'While the Cidhall family is undoubtedly powerful, Roland...' Baphomet persisted in his attempts to redirect the conversation."

1014.m_mText: "'The Roland family is stingy beyond belief. They call themselves the Lords of the Plains, but they don't have a clue about give and take. The only ones worse off are the Ganelon family—those wolf pups barely understand the concept of money!'"

1015.m_mText: "Baphomet was sinking into despair, realizing that this meeting was likely to end on Bella's relentless prattle."

1016.m_mText: "'Enough!' Baphomet cut in sharply. 'What I want to discuss is how we can create more powerful vessels to counter the growing strength of other powerful families.'"

1017.m_mText: "A hush fell over the group. They began to fidget and cast their eyes about, clearly disinterested in the topic. After all, they had rehashed similar issues countless times before."

1018.m_mText: "'What are you trying to do?' Gilrain suddenly snapped to attention, eyes narrowing."

1019.m_mText: "Baphomet would have worn a mocking expression, if only his armor allowed such displays. 'It's quite simple. We must create a perfect vessel for the Matriarch, and cultivate more powerful elders.'"

1020.m_mText: "'We'll employ Bloodline Transfusion to train exceptional warriors from other families, using their ancestral blood. Then, through the Embrace, we'll transform these warriors into Bloodborn.'"

1021.m_mText: "'You... Is this twisted idea born from what you did to me?' Gilrain sneered through gritted teeth."

1022.m_mText: "'Indeed,' Baphomet declared with a note of pride in his voice. 'After all, you stand unique among the current elders—the only one from another family, and the only true Bloodborn among us.'"

1023.m_mText: "'In that case, even if we can't call it a 'perfect being,' it should suffice to address our current predicament.'"

1024.m_mText: "Gilrain's expression turned cold. 'So which family do you intend to use for the Transfusion? You'd be hard-pressed to find anyone in the Cidhall family stronger than me.'"

1025.m_mText: "'There's a girl from the Ganelon family who's rumored to possess considerable power.'"

1026.m_mText: "'However, obtaining their ancestral blood would likely require venturing into the forbidden grounds, and that Gravekeeper Clive Ganelon is no pushover.'"

1027.m_mText: "Baphomet explains, 'The ancestral blood of the Roland family, the Horse, is equally elusive. They bury their dead wherever they please across the great plains.'"

1028.m_mText: "'What about the Carrelle family, the 'Eagle,' and the Ruthven family, the 'Serpent'?'"

1029.m_mText: "'Those two pathetic families?' Gilrain's voice dripped with contempt. 'Those weaklings rely on hidden arrows and poison to do their dirty work. They're utterly worthless in a real battle.'"

1030.m_mText: "'Among the warriors of the major families, who actually has the greatest individual strength?' Bella asked with genuine curiosity."

1031.m_mText: "'Given the current state of the conflicts, Florent Griffith is undoubtedly the strongest warrior. However, he has never faced Friedrich Roland in combat, who is now a Bell Ringer of the Church.'"

1032.m_mText: "'So, one could say that the Griffith and Roland families stand on equal footing.'"

1033.m_mText: "Bella, however, disagreed: 'The Griffiths may rule the ice plains, but they're no match for the Rolands and their warhorses. If I were betting, I'd put my money on the Rolands any day.'"

1034.m_mText: "'Victory with warhorses isn't a fair comparison,' Morain argued. 'We should evaluate them under equal conditions: on foot, without relying on enhancements like the Blood of Light.'"

1035.m_mText: "'You're just bitter because Friedrich beat you for the Bell Ringer position!' Bella ruthlessly exposed Gilrain's true motives. 'That's why you're trying so hard to belittle the Roland family!'"

1036.m_mText: "'That's right,' Gilrain declared, laying bare his true feelings. 'If anyone's to be compared to the Lion, it should be us, the Bull. The Horse doesn't even deserve to be mentioned in the same breath!'"

1037.m_mText: "'Now, now, let's all calm down. A good merchant never wants to drive away a potential customer.'"

2001001.m_mText: "'Our presence here stems from the fact that Bloodline Transfusion has long been our primary means of nurturing powerful vessels. However, it appears we've now reached the very limits of this method.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'It's quite straightforward,' Gilrain explained, stating what everyone already knew. 'We've been consistently using the Matriarch's bloodline for the transfusions. We have long reached its limit.'"

2001003.m_mText: "To transcend this limitation, we must seek out an older Ancestry,' Bella posited. She then added, 'Have we thoroughly searched the Ancestral Vault? I've heard whispers of strange sounds emanating from there recently.'"

2001004.m_mText: "'That place now stands barren,' the Baphomet intoned, his words heavy with disappointment."

2002001.m_mText: "'If we could find an older Ancestral bloodline—Dracula's being ideal—that would solve our problem.'"

2002002.m_mText: "'You might as well declare war on all the major families,' Gilrain retorted. 'If we had that much power, we wouldn't be fretting over increasing our strength.'"

2002003.m_mText: "Another option would be to find other Ancestries older than the Matriarch, but the Puppet Association has yet to uncover any leads,' Bella added with a sigh."

2003001.m_mText: "'There is another option: we could attempt a Bloodline Transfusion using the bloodline of other families.'"

2003002.m_mText: "'What? How would that work?' Bella asked, tilting her head in confusion. 'Wouldn't the bloodlines be completely incompatible?'"

2003003.m_mText: "In truth, the Bathory family was once an ordinary family on the continent, until one of them caught Dracula's eye and was transformed into a Bloodborn."

1.m_mText: "It is often said that we see may not be the truth, what we know may not be fact."

1002.m_mText: "As Selena and Van Helsing secretly entered the Bathory family's Ancestral Vault, they could never have imagined what awaited them."

1003.m_mText: "Rumors of this mysterious chamber spread like wildfire within the Silver Cross. Van Helsing remained ever vigilant, dreading the possible return of a powerful Bloodborn Ancestry."

1004.m_mText: "Once again, they infiltrated the Bathory Castle to investigate the Ancestral Vault, only to cross paths with Noah during his after-dinner stroll."

1005.m_mText: "In truth, the protagonist’s presence was far from coincidental. The longer he resided in the castle, the more the mysterious chamber captivated his curiosity. Thus, the three agreed to explore it together."

1006.m_mText: "Upon infiltrating, however, they found that guarding the vault's entrance was neither a powerful seal nor a terrifying monster—but an elderly man with a large key ring dangling from his waist."

1007.m_mText: "'Should we kill him?' Selena whispered, her eyes on the drowsy guard as she quietly drew her crossbow."

1008.m_mText: "But Noah simply approached the old guard. 'Excuse me, sir...'"

1009.m_mText: "Before Noah could finish, the old guard looked up sharply. 'Tell your two accomplices to come out as well. Your incessant whispering was starting to annoy me.'"

1010.m_mText: "Noah's face flushed with embarrassment. 'My apologies,' he mumbled, turning back to beckon his companions."

1011.m_mText: "As the three stood before the guard, they resembled children who were caught red-handed."

1012.m_mText: "'You're here to investigate the Ancestral Vault?' the guard asked. 'Is it because of the sounds coming from inside?'"

1014.m_mText: "'I was becoming concerned too,' the guard admitted. 'If you knew its history, you'd understand—there shouldn't be any sounds coming from the vault at all.'"

1015.m_mText: "'I actually know a bit about it,' Noah said. 'I've done extensive research in the archives before coming here.'"

1016.m_mText: "It's said that during the Crimson Inquisition, several Ancestries with unique Blood Powers hid in the vault, along with some prisoners of war.'"

1017.m_mText: "Isaac asked urgently, 'Did any of those Ancestries leave the vault? And what became of the prisoners?'"

1018.m_mText: "The guard revealed an unsettling expression: 'I don't know. After all, it's not just some vault, but an incomprehensibly vast space.'"

1019.m_mText: "'As the Bloodborn were busy dealing with the Crimson Inquisition, they nearly forgot about their captives. They failed to provide fresh food and water.'"

1020.m_mText: "'Many of the prisoners were once high-ranking officials and noblemen, unable to endure the rancid food and foul water. Some succumbed to illness, while others chose to end their own lives.'"

1021.m_mText: "When the Ancestries entered the vault, they were shocked to find only one survivor among their food.'"

1022.m_mText: "It was a tenacious young girl who had managed to survive by any means necessary. Some of the Ancestries even suspected she wasn't actually an important figure at all, but an impostor.'"

1023.m_mText: "In such dire circumstances, the girl's background would have been irrelevant. The Ancestries must have turned on each other, fighting over the only remaining scrap of food! This explains why so many never emerged from the vault!'"

1024.m_mText: "The guard continued, his eyes even more clouded with age as he gazed into the distance: 'The Ancestries are powerful beings, not so easily starved to death. Not all Bloodborn relish drinking blood either, as evidenced by the one standing next to you.'"

1025.m_mText: "'Hmph, you expect me to believe that?' Isaac scoffed, his face etched with disdain."

1026.m_mText: "However, as in many clichéd tales, one Ancestry fell for the girl. He soon noticed some of his fellow Ancestrals struggling more and more to suppress their growing hunger."

1027.m_mText: "Inevitably, a battle erupted. No one knows how many Ancestries perished—perhaps even more than during the Crimson Inquisition. Quite the irony, wouldn't you say?'"

1028.m_mText: "'Oh, just get to the point already!' Isaac snapped, his patience clearly spent."

1029.m_mText: "The guard's pale lips curled in a dry chuckle. 'A cliché tale begets a cliché ending. In the end, the Ancestry who defied the others fled into the crypt's depths with the girl.'"

2001001.m_mText: "'No.' Noah whispered firmly. 'If we kill him, it'll alert others that someone entered the vault.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'He's just some random Bloodborn,' Van Helsing scoffed. 'His death will be forgotten just like this place.'"

2001003.m_mText: "But Noah remained adamant: 'No. We're here to investigate the vault, not to kill indiscriminately.'"

2001004.m_mText: "Isaac shot Noah an icy glare. 'Don't forget, in our eyes, most Bloodborn are far from innocent.' With a swift gesture to Selena, he fired his crossbow at the guard."

2001005.m_mText: "In a flash, Noah's sword cut through the air, cleaving the bolt in two. 'I said no.' Now that's our protagonist in action!"

2002001.m_mText: "'Fine, let's get it over with.' Noah said resolutely."

2002002.m_mText: "'Wait!' To everyone's surprise, it was Van Helsing who objected."

2002003.m_mText: "'Wait?' Selena stared at Van Helsing in confusion."

2002004.m_mText: "'Killing him without cause is not justice,' Van Helsing reasoned, though deep down, he knew he was merely opposing Noah out of habit."

2003001.m_mText: "'It seems the recent disturbances in the Ancestral Vault were likely caused by this traitorous Ancestry,' Noah deduced."

2003002.m_mText: "'That's very possible,' the guard agreed. 'While the girl is unlikely to have lived this long, the traitor may return.'"

2003003.m_mText: "'But why didn't he turn her into a vampire through the Embrace?' Selena asked innocently. 'Then they could have been together forever.'"

2003004.m_mText: "'And who's to say that after the Embrace, the girl would share her master's aversion to blood?' The guard's words were tinged with bitterness."

2004001.m_mText: "The Ancestry responsible for the noises from the cellar... could he have already left?' Noah speculated."

2004002.m_mText: "'Right, how else would he know with such certainty?' Isaac chimed in."

2004003.m_mText: "'Perhaps,' the guard mused. 'He is one of the condemned of the Bathory family, and that accursed cellar serves as his eternal prison.'"

1.m_mText: "In truth, our understanding of this world is woefully limited. Time and again, phenomena emerge that defy our imagination, shattering not just our perceptions, but those of every character in our tale."

1002.m_mText: "It is as though an unseen force is at work, systematically dismantling our meticulously constructed view of the world, leaving in its wake an atmosphere of dread."

1003.m_mText: "The Hall of Opulence, one of the few dimly lit chambers in the Bathory castle, found Cain speaking softly to a portrait on the wall: 'Tell me, do you still remember the promise we made all those years ago?'"

1004.m_mText: "Amidst the hall's array of rare specimens and curiosities, this portrait stood out."

1005.m_mText: "'Of course I remember,' came a reply from the painting. Cain, it seemed, hadn't been talking to himself after all. The portrait—none other than that of Limine Bathory, the Matriarch herself—had spoken."

1006.m_mText: "'The foretold day draws near,' Cain continued, his voice heavy with concern. 'Will you really disappear?'"

1007.m_mText: "A chilling, otherworldly laugh emanated from the portrait. 'What makes you think I wouldn't?'"

1008.m_mText: "'Should you break your promise, I will stop at nothing...'"

1010.m_mText: "For only the second time in all his years, Cain, the epitome of composure, felt utterly powerless. Never before had he been mocked as 'ignorant,' yet now, the term fit with stinging accuracy!"

1011.m_mText: "In the distance, the sound of two girls arguing interrupted Cain's train of thought. He turned to see their silhouettes dancing in the lamplight, stretching and shrinking with each heated exchange."

1012.m_mText: "Empousa's indignant voice cut through the air: 'This is all your fault! I'm stuck here cleaning because of you!'"

1013.m_mText: "Lamia sneered with unbridled satisfaction, 'Oh, don't be so petty. You're just too dim-witted to realize you had a chance to escape.'"

1014.m_mText: "'Escape? I wouldn't be here if I had a way out!' Empousa cried out with frustration. When the incident unfolded, she had been trapped in the elevator and unwittingly became Lamia's accomplice."

1015.m_mText: "As for what Lamia did that angered the elders—that's another tale for another time. After all, every story has its bounds."

1016.m_mText: "Lamia was the first to spot Cain and wasted no time in calling him out. 'Cain! Why are you loitering here instead of attending to your duties?'"

1017.m_mText: "Cain replied with a smirk, 'Taking time to appreciate the fine arts after work is a way to discover new inspirations.'"

1018.m_mText: "Lamia gazed at the Matriarch's portrait as an inexplicable emotion stirred within her. 'And this painting,' she remarked, 'it provides you with inspiration?'"

1019.m_mText: "'Doubly so—from both the sublime artistry and the Matriarch herself,' Cain replied."

1020.m_mText: "The two girls recoiled in shock, for this was the first time they had heard the portrait speak."

1021.m_mText: "'Quiet!' Cain's eyes blazed with fury at the image of Limine. 'You promised never to utter a word in the presence of others!'"

1022.m_mText: "The portrait erupted into another bout of devious laughter. 'But my previous words were quite serious!'"

1023.m_mText: "'What is that thing?' Empousa cried out in terror."

1024.m_mText: "'Don't overreact,' Lamia said, trying to maintain her facade of composure in front of her sister. 'It's just a magical painting.'"

1025.m_mText: "'That's right,' Cain affirmed. 'It's merely an art piece created through alchemy.'"

1026.m_mText: "'Oh? And will you claim that I'm also one of your creations, O illustrious Grand Alchemist?' The Matriarch's visage taunted."

1027.m_mText: "'Fine! This is neither a product of alchemy nor any known magic in this world. It is something... unknown,' Cain unwillingly admitted."

1028.m_mText: "'Something unknown...' Empousa echoed as a strange calm began to settle over her."

1029.m_mText: "'There are no unknowns in this world,' Lamia scoffed while trying to keep her composure. 'You simply don't know, but I bet someone does.'"

1030.m_mText: "'I don't know?' Cain smiled bitterly. 'Then allow me to tell you the origin of this painting.'"

1031.m_mText: "'Truth is, these portraits will suddenly appear one day, despite the subject never remembering ever sitting down to have it painted. And if the subject were to gaze upon their portrait, they will see their true self.'"

1032.m_mText: "'Isn't that just like looking in a mirror?' Empousa blurted out, before regretting her words."

1033.m_mText: "'Not quite. Mirrors often show us an unfamiliar face. This painting, however, offers a dynamic journey of self-discovery, one that's intimately tied to your imagination.'"

1034.m_mText: "'It simultaneously reveals your true self and the self warped by your own perception.'"

1035.m_mText: "'I don't understand a word you're saying, Cain!' Lamia bursted out."

1036.m_mText: "'People often look at mirrors hoping to see the person they imagine themselves to be, only to be disappointed. But not when looking at these portraits.'"

1037.m_mText: "'Within them, you will see the ideal version of yourself, and be mesmerized with self-adoration. But soon, horrifying things will begin to unfold.'"

1038.m_mText: "'What kind of horrifying things,' Empousa asked."

1039.m_mText: "'You see, the image in the portrait will begin to change and distort, and the person before it will as well.'"

1040.m_mText: "'Change into what?' Lamia asked, struggling to mask her fear as she met the Matriarch's gaze in the portrait—a chilling look that made her quiver."

2001001.m_mText: "'No amount of your flattery will reach the Matriarch's ears.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'And what if they did?' The painting on the wall suddenly interjected."

2002001.m_mText: "'Cain, I can't believe you have the nerve to say something so shameless.'"

2002002.m_mText: "'It's simply out of the utmost respect for the Matriarch,' Cain replied solemnly."

2002003.m_mText: "'And fear.' The painting on the wall interjected."

2003001.m_mText: "'Cain, I have to say, your words are truly revolting.'"

2003002.m_mText: "'See, Cain?' The painting on the wall suddenly spoke. 'Even these children have noticed your abnormal behavior.'"

1.m_mText: "The celestial dance of stars whispers the ebb and flow of fate, etching omens of things to come. Sages, with eyes turned skyward each night, unravel the tapestry of tomorrow."

1002.m_mText: "'What a load of nonsense!' Empousa scoffed, her disdain for such starry-eyed notions palpable."

1003.m_mText: "Jestel, ever the pragmatist, stood at the Observatory's threshold, her face a canvas of utter bewilderment. 'Then what's the point of us being here?'"

1004.m_mText: "At this moment, four individuals arrived at the Observatory: Empousa and Jestel, accompanied by our protagonist Noah and the witch Aiona."

1005.m_mText: "Just then, a shooting star streaked across the sky above the Observatory. Only one person witnessed this fleeting marvel. Among the four now inside the Observatory, who could be that fortunate soul?"

1006.m_mText: "'Oh, a shooting star!' Our protagonist's exclamation sounded just like that of an insignificant side character."

1009.m_mText: "'Just there.' Well, that's our witch who always seems to have a glimpse of the future."

1010.m_mText: "Jestel eagerly crossed her fingers like a child: 'Quick, make a wish! Even though I'm the last of the Aegis line, I still hope there's a chance for our family to be reborn!'"

1011.m_mText: "Yet, even in this realm, the act of wishing upon a shooting star remains nothing more than superstition."

1012.m_mText: "'That's far from mere superstition! There's a documented case of someone's wish being granted by a shooting star.'"

1013.m_mText: "Alas, even if one's wish did come to fruition, it was but a twist of fate, a mere coincidence."

1014.m_mText: "'In ages past, a princess of the Berde Kingdom a prince of the Yegar Kingdom cast their wishes upon the same celestial wanderer on one fateful night, both yearning for true love and eternal companionship.'"

1015.m_mText: "A tale as whimsical as any children's fable."

1016.m_mText: "'Eventually, they fell in love and married, uniting two Kingdoms that had once been sworn enemies.'"

1017.m_mText: "Yet, such royal alliances are but common stratagems in the game of thrones. Surely, it was naught but coincidence!"

1018.m_mText: "'Maybe... we should make a wish too, if we see another shooting star,' Noah suggested hesitantly."

1019.m_mText: "'Hehe.' Empousa's lips curled into a self-satisfied smirk. Despite teasing the amnesiac protagonist, she felt not an ounce of remorse."

1020.m_mText: "'Actually, many ancient texts warn that shooting stars bring disaster!' Empousa declared with merciless glee!"

1021.m_mText: "Jestel, of course, couldn't accept this view. 'How can two people finding true love be a disaster?' she protested."

1022.m_mText: "'Oh, but it was a disaster. The marriage alliance between the Berde and Yegar Kingdoms became a threat to the kingdom in the west.'"

1024.m_mText: "'In the end, both kingdoms fell to King Johan the Red's eastern campaign,' Empousa continued nonchalantly. 'The princess and prince? Oh, they were sent to the guillotine just a year after their marriage.'"

2001001.m_mText: "'It was Aiona's suggestion.' Noah was the first one Aiona had located."

2001002.m_mText: "'A celestial messenger shall arrive tonight.' The witch, naturally, wouldn't deign to provide a straightforward answer, preserving her air of mystery. Did you grasp her meaning? Don't fret if it eludes you."

2002001.m_mText: "'Empousa suggested we all stargaze together.' Though in truth, her proposal was for a more... intimate gathering."

2002002.m_mText: "Empousa's flippant justification was: 'Well, everyone's been very bored lately.'"

2002003.m_mText: "Truth be told, Empousa had been battling a bout of boredom lately and had secretly been devouring books about the stars."

2003001.m_mText: "'I thought this place could use a bit of tidying up.' Noah finally unveiled his decidedly mundane motivation."

2003002.m_mText: "Learning it was Noah's idea, Jestel sighed resignedly, 'I've told you before, Noah. It's impossible to keep a castle this huge clean.'"

2004001.m_mText: "Do you even need to ask? It's our protagonist, of course!"

2005001.m_mText: "Do you even need to ask? It's our protagonist, of course!"

2006001.m_mText: "Do you even need to ask? It's our protagonist, of course!"

2007001.m_mText: "'It sounds like a fabricated beautiful fairy tale.'"

2007002.m_mText: "Jestel looked a bit disappointed. 'I suppose it could be... After all, I only heard it as a child.'"

2007003.m_mText: "'No, it's actual history,' Empousa cut in abruptly, catching even Noah off guard."

2008001.m_mText: "'There's no other way to describe this but as a coincidence.'"

2008002.m_mText: "'Within many coincidences lies an element of inevitability.' Aiona's cryptic words left the others even more bewildered."

2009001.m_mText: "'It could be nothing more than a fabrication to facilitate a marriage alliance between two Kingdoms.' Noah knew it was time for Jestel to be exposed to the harsh realities of politics."

2009002.m_mText: "'That's possible, but many historical records document this event,' Empousa countered. It seems she came well-prepared for this discussion!"

1.m_mText: "In this world, true coincidence is but an illusion. Even fate itself is a puppet, its strings pulled by unseen hands lurking in shadow. We revel in fleeting moments of fortune, blind to the grand deception unfolding around us."

1002.m_mText: "Inspired by tales from their master, Van Helsing, Piera, and Nicole embarked on a journey to the Crescent Garden, hoping to uncover the hidden truths of alchemy within its bounds."

1003.m_mText: "But the Crescent Garden proved a bitter disappointment. The church lay in ruins, its crumbling walls suffocated by an unyielding embrace of rose vines."

1004.m_mText: "'So this is why it's called the Crescent Garden,' Piera remarked to her junior disciples, a wry smile playing on her lips. 'The roses have formed a perfect crescent around the ruins.'"

1005.m_mText: "Isaac Van Helsing, the youngest of the group, frowned like an old man. 'In such a damp environment, any books would surely be beyond salvation by now.'"

1006.m_mText: "Nicole, the middle disciple, offered a contrasting view. 'Many of the Church's texts are safeguarded by special measures. They wouldn't succumb to decay so easily.'"

1007.m_mText: "'Even with its proximity to the Bathory's castle,' Isaac persisted in his pessimism, 'this site couldn't have escaped the attention of clandestine looters.'"

1008.m_mText: "'Let's go,' Piera decided. 'No point wasting time here. We'll go in and see for ourselves.'"

1009.m_mText: "The trio moved between ruined walls and rose bushes, using moonlight to find their footing while carefully avoiding the sharp thorns hidden along the stems."

1010.m_mText: "Fortunately, their master had provided them with an old map of the church from its time. Although the building was now unrecognizable, the map at least helped them locate the library's position."

1011.m_mText: "'The only advantage is all these new shortcuts,' Isaac quipped as they climbed over a collapsed wall."

1012.m_mText: "Nicole's eyes darted around. 'I can't shake the feeling that we're not alone here. There must be others.'"

1013.m_mText: "Piera, the senior disciple with the most battlefield experience, had already pinpointed the source of the strange feeling. 'Over there! Everyone, be on guard!'"

1014.m_mText: "Just then, Van Helsing noticed dozens of books stacked in the corner. 'Look! There are books over there!'"

1015.m_mText: "As Isaac reached for the stack of books, Piera suddenly grabbed his arm. Following her gaze, he witnessed the wall itself writhing and contorting. Purple roses bloomed and withered in an unnatural, pulsating cycle."

1016.m_mText: "'To use the power of time manipulation in a sacred place of the Church is utter blasphemy!' Isaac's shock quickly gave way to a surge of righteous fury."

1017.m_mText: "Undaunted by the overwhelming odds, the trio spread out with trained precision. Like young lions on the hunt, they silently stalked their formidable prey."

1018.m_mText: "Under the moonlight, they came upon an even more out-of-place metal instrument. Even the moonlight twisted and coiled around it, as if being inexorably drawn into its otherworldly form."

1019.m_mText: "Before the instrument stood a black-haired man, with a subtle mockery exuding from the corner of his mouth."

1020.m_mText: "The black-haired man turned to face them. 'Curiosity is the crucible of growth for the youth, but it can also bring a premature end.'"

1021.m_mText: "'Cain,' the black-haired man introduced. 'Steward of the Bathory family.'"

1022.m_mText: "Isaac exclaimed with sharp accusation: 'How dare you conduct experiments with time in this sacred place? This is blasphemy against the goddess!'"

1023.m_mText: "'Look at these ruins around you. Faith collapsed here long ago,' Cain retorted. 'How can one blaspheme against what no longer exists?'"

1024.m_mText: "'The power of time is a divine right, not to be wielded by mortal hands,' Nicole interjected, cutting straight to the point."

1025.m_mText: "Cain smirked. 'That's precisely why I'm here, helping myself to the last scraps of the goddess's power.'"

1026.m_mText: "'We're leaving,' Piera cut in firmly. 'Our only purpose here is to find useful texts. Whatever he's doing is irrelevant to our mission.'"

1027.m_mText: "'A wise decision,' Cain nodded approvingly. 'If you're seeking specific texts, perhaps I can... guide your search.'"

1028.m_mText: "'We seek texts or treatises concerning the art of alchemy.'"

1029.m_mText: "'Some of those books were taken by the Church, while I brought the rest back to the Bathory's castle,' Cain said, as his hair swayed despite there being no wind."

1030.m_mText: "'Those belong to the Church!' Isaac exclaimed vehemently."

1031.m_mText: "'Oh? So you speak for the Church now?' Cain asked, his voice laced with skepticism."

1032.m_mText: "Isaac desperately wanted to affirm, but he couldn't bring himself to utter the lie."

1033.m_mText: "'Since there are no books here, we should take our leave,' said Piera. The eldest in the group was always aware of the dangers at stake."

1034.m_mText: "'This sacred ground once echoed with the Bathory family's devout prayers to the goddess Aeon,' Cain said. 'Do you know why it now lies in ruins?'"

1035.m_mText: "A silence fell over the three as each attempted to unravel Cain's intentions behind this unexpected history lesson."

1036.m_mText: "'The goddess's repeated treachery against the Bathory family left them with no choice but to seek an alliance with Dracula.'"

1038.m_mText: "'The Bathory family's loyalty was once unquestionable. When the goddess commanded them to cede a portion of their lands to their despised rivals, the Ganelon family, they obeyed, surrendering territory to those contemptible mongrels.'"

2001001.m_mText: "The inexperienced Isaac darted towards the black-haired man, forcing his senior sisters into action as well."

2001002.m_mText: "The dark-haired man suddenly let out a soft sigh."

2001003.m_mText: "The three suddenly halted in their semi-circular formation around him, as if struck by an otherworldly force emanating from his being, leaving them gasping for air."

2001004.m_mText: "Struggling to find his voice, Isaac finally choked out, 'Are you... one of Bathory's people?'"

2002001.m_mText: "Sensing the overwhelming threat, Piera immediately signaled the others to retreat."

2002002.m_mText: "Van Helsing and Nicole began to retreat, as cautiously as when they had come."

2002003.m_mText: "However, they discovered that everything around them began to distort, while their own bodies seemed to grow and shrink erratically."

2003001.m_mText: "'Are you... from the Bathory family?' Nicole suddenly asked."

2003002.m_mText: "When facing a vast disparity in power, this was perhaps the best course of action."

1.m_mText: "Time beautifies our memories, yet also distorts them. It is our inability to return to the past that makes the solace of remembrance so essential."

1002.m_mText: "Hati stared at the crude key in her hand, shocked by how much older and more rust-covered it was than in her memory. Would it still manage to open the wooden door before her? Or would it simply snap off in the keyhole?"

1003.m_mText: "'Hey, you dumb mutt, don't tell me you brought the wrong key?' Empousa's sharp words instantly shattered the melancholy that had been welling up in Hati's heart."

1004.m_mText: "'You bloodsucking pest...' Hati began, but couldn't muster a proper comeback. Instead, she used the key to unlock the door of Mouret Mill, hesitating as she took just one step inside."

1005.m_mText: "Empousa peeked in from behind the Hati, her nose wrinkling in disgust. 'Oh my, there's flour coating every surface! These hygiene conditions are absolutely dreadful!'"

1006.m_mText: "'Does it really matter?' Ami's voice called from behind them. She had been wandering through the wheat fields, which explained her delayed arrival."

1007.m_mText: "'Oh Ami, of course you wouldn't understand, having spent your life at sea,' Empousa said with an air of superiority. 'A mill needs regular cleaning, otherwise it becomes a haven for rats and insects.'"

1008.m_mText: "'Stop showing off knowledge you've picked up from books,' Hati called out Empousa. 'Cleaning a mill requires a lot of water and is usually done after the harvest season. It's not something that happens frequently.'"

1009.m_mText: "'How could anyone possibly stomach bread made with flour from such a filthy place?' Empousa exclaimed, her cheeks flushing with indignation."

1010.m_mText: "Hati glanced up at the idle gears above, powered by the windmill. 'Of course we can eat it. The bread is mostly dark, but it's quite tasty. After all, this is the only mill in all of Mouret town.'"

1011.m_mText: "'What? A town this size with just one mill?!' Empousa gasped, her eyes wide with astonishment."

1012.m_mText: "'Our ancestors were hunters, not farmers at all,' Hati said, noticing Empousa's surprise. 'Don't tell me you've never read about the Ganelon family's history in your books?'"

1013.m_mText: "'I-I couldn't care less about the history of you stupid wolves!' Empousa stammered, her cheeks flushed with a mix of embarrassment and defiance."

1014.m_mText: "'I suppose the young lady only reads what interests her.' Ami glanced into the mill, quickly grasped its workings, and just as swiftly lost interest."

1015.m_mText: "'One year, a devastating forest fire prevented Mouret from stockpiling enough winter provisions. The town faced the grim prospect of mass starvation.'"

1016.m_mText: "'Desperate, the Ganelon family sought aid from major families across the continent, even appealing to the Church. But all turned them away, citing various reasons.'"

1017.m_mText: "'Couldn't they just buy food?' Ami asked, bewildered. Her experience observing Goldland doing business made this situation utterly incomprehensible."

1018.m_mText: "'They clearly had no concept of financial planning,' Empousa scoffed, her voice dripping with disdain and unwarranted superiority."

1019.m_mText: "Hati continued, 'Just as the Ganelon family had resigned themselves to relocating the entire town, a heavy snowfall descended, as if determined to drive everyone into despair.'"

1020.m_mText: "'But then, someone arrived with sacks of flour and taught the Ganelon family how to bake black bread.'"

1021.m_mText: "'That's how the Ganelon family survived that winter. Afterward, they began cultivating crops on their own land.' Hati turned her gaze towards Empousa."

1022.m_mText: "'And the only ones who came to the Ganelon family's aid in their hour of need were the Bathory family.'"

1023.m_mText: "'Why?' Empousa exclaimed, even more astonished than Hati had been when her father first recounted this tale. 'Was this before the Bathorys began their research into immortality?'"

1024.m_mText: "'No,' Hati revealed, her voice tinged with disbelief at her own words. 'It happened after the two families had been locked in a prolonged war.'"

1025.m_mText: "'But why?' Empousa pressed, her confusion deepening with each revelation."

1026.m_mText: "Hati said, with evident reluctance, 'According to the explanation given by the Bathory family head at that time, they were concerned that if the Ganelon family became too weak, the Church might turn its attention directly to the Bathory family.'"

1027.m_mText: "'But weren't the Ganelon family worried that the Bathory family might sabotage the flour?' Ami asked, though she already knew how it had turned out."

1028.m_mText: "Empousa exclaimed eagerly, 'And wasn't that a perfect opportunity to bring the Ganelon family over to the Bloodborn side?'"

1029.m_mText: "'But I think neither family truly wanted to be on the same side as the other,' Hati observed, much to her surprise finding agreement from both Empousa and Ami."

1030.m_mText: "'To ensure the Ganelon family wouldn't face starvation in the following winter, the Bathory family even joined in the farming efforts.'"

1031.m_mText: "'Then, after the wheat had ripened, the Bathory family helped transform this mill. It was originally just a modest hut on a steep slope, but look at it now.'"

1032.m_mText: "'This story can't possibly be true, can it?' Empousa said with a pronounced pout. 'I wouldn't believe it even if my life depended on it. How could these two families ever have gotten along?'"

1033.m_mText: "'Based on my understanding, fabricating such a story wouldn't benefit anyone. At most, it would only serve to strain relations between the Ganelon family, the Church, and other families.'"

1034.m_mText: "'Many in the Ganelon family know this story, yet they still maintain their faith and support the Church. As for the Bathory family, however...'"

1035.m_mText: "'Well, I've never heard anyone mention this before,' Empousa chimed in."

1036.m_mText: "'I believe it's because the Ganelon family, having learned farming, expanded Mouret and increased its population. This led to them becoming a major force in the subsequent 'Crimson Inquisition'.'"

1037.m_mText: "'No wonder this isn't mentioned in the Bathory family records,' Empousa exclaimed. 'We inadvertently cultivated such a powerful enemy for ourselves—it's utterly humiliating!'"

1038.m_mText: "'Yes. Legend has it that the Bathory family head who spearheaded the effort to aid Ganelon vehemently cursed the Ganelon family before he was killed.'"

1039.m_mText: "'A curse for the extinction of the entire Ganelon family?' Ami remarked with a wry smile. 'Well, it seems that curse has certainly come to fruition now.'"

1040.m_mText: "'No,' Hati said with a bitter smile. 'He cursed the Ganelon family, saying that one day they would be unable to harvest from their own estate.'"

2001001.m_mText: "'But that curse is meaningless anyway. Even if the Ganelon family hadn't been wiped out, a heavy downpour could just as easily ruin a bountiful harvest.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'Hmph, I guess that's all the hatred that family head could muster for the Ganelon family.'"

2001003.m_mText: "Hati suddenly looked troubled. 'But there's something I just can't wrap my head around. The Ganelon family's defining trait is loyalty! How could they possibly betray someone who helped them?'"

2001004.m_mText: "'You're not wrong. The Ganelon family has always been loyal to the Church above all else.' It was impossible to tell whether Ami's words were meant as praise or sarcasm."

2002001.m_mText: "'I never imagined the curse would actually come true after all these years.'"

2002002.m_mText: "'Tch, you call this fulfilling the curse?' Empousa scoffed, clearly unsatisfied."

2002003.m_mText: "'Could there still be a way to ensure the curse is never fulfilled?' Ami's words plunged both listeners into deep contemplation."

1.m_mText: "Have you ever had this experience... You stumble upon something long forgotten, triggering a memory you'd almost lost. Yet, in that moment of recollection, you find the memory itself becoming strangely unfamiliar."

1002.m_mText: "'You mean Ami?' Hati turned to answer the two girls behind her. 'She visited once before, but now she absolutely refuses to come back.'"

1003.m_mText: "'Why won't she hang out with us?' Empousa grumbled, contemplating ways to drag Ami out of the Bathory castle."

1004.m_mText: "'Perhaps you should worry more about your castle's food supplies,' Ressa teased, hitting Empousa's sore spot: Ami was eating them out of house and home."

1005.m_mText: "'Who'd have thought the Ganelon family's harvest would end up as emergency rations for the Bathorys,' Empousa mused, torn between relief and sadness."

1006.m_mText: "To protect farmers within the Bathory territory from wolf attacks during the harvest, Hati had been making daily trips to Mouret."

1007.m_mText: "This continued until all the wheat had been ground into flour and transported back to the Bathory lands. Empousa and Ressa, meanwhile, were there purely for the excitement."

1008.m_mText: "Now the mill's windmill no longer spun idly. Its interlocking gears drove the millstone, steadily grinding out sack after sack of easily storable flour."

1009.m_mText: "Hati glanced up at the mill and said, 'Would you all mind doing me a favor?'"

1010.m_mText: "'Sounds like a minor thing from the way you're talking,' Ressa replied."

1011.m_mText: "Empousa pouted. 'Ressa, that sounds like you're trying to refuse without actually saying no.'"

1012.m_mText: "'We can't just say yes to something when we don't know what we're getting into,' Ressa said firmly."

1013.m_mText: "'I want to climb to the top of the mill tonight,' Hati revealed. 'There's something I need to find up there.'"

1014.m_mText: "Empousa glanced up at the top of the mill with curiosity. 'Are you afraid of heights or the dark?'"

1015.m_mText: "'Neither. It's just too hard to climb up on my own.'"

1016.m_mText: "'How hard is it?' Ressa asked with concern."

1017.m_mText: "'With three people, it's really quite straightforward,' Hati said, leaving the other two completely baffled."

1018.m_mText: "On the mill's final night of operation, Hati used a wrench to disengage the gears connecting the windmill to the mechanism below. However, she deliberately left the switch that locked the windmill's rotation in place."

1019.m_mText: "This was to eliminate any chance of being struck by the windmill as they climbed. But this action could potentially reduce the windmill's durability to the point where it could break before the next group came to take it over."

1020.m_mText: "As Ressa and Empousa prepared to ascend to the roof, they were met with an unpleasant surprise: the ladder was broken."

1021.m_mText: "Thinking quickly, Empousa transformed into a bat and flew to the roof while Ressa climbed onto Hati's shoulders to deliver a rope to the top."

1022.m_mText: "As Hati got the roof after the other two, she gazed upward to see the full moon slowly disappearing behind a veil of ominous clouds."

1023.m_mText: "'Looks like rain's on its way,' Ressa observed, voicing the unwelcome truth no one wanted to hear. On the bright side, they had managed to complete the harvest just in time."

1024.m_mText: "Before Hati could reveal why they were on the roof, the sky was suddenly split by a bolt of lightning. A deafening crash of thunder followed, causing stone tiles to break loose and tumble from the roof."

1025.m_mText: "Empousa let out a scream and hurled herself into Ressa's arms."

1026.m_mText: "'I didn't think a Bloodborn would be afraid of lightning,' Ressa said with a gentle, comforting smile."

1027.m_mText: "'It's just... I've never been this close to lightning in the open before, and... and...'"

1028.m_mText: "Hati interjected: 'I recall reading in the family records that a Bathory ancestor was killed after being struck by lightning. Perhaps that explains Empousa's fear.'"

1029.m_mText: "'Could it have happened during the castle's construction?' Ressa mused. 'The Bathory castle stands impressively tall and is outfitted with an extensive array of lightning rods. Perhaps a lesson learned from that tragedy?'"

1030.m_mText: "'It happened during one of the castle's expansions,' Empousa's now calm voice replied. 'That particular individual was consumed by an insatiable obsession to reach the moon, which manifested in relentlessly expanding the castle up toward the sky.'"

1031.m_mText: "'Furthermore, he became an extraordinary architect during his long life. The observatory in the castle was his masterpiece.'"

1032.m_mText: "'Yet his ambition remained unfulfilled. He yearned to construct an even loftier tower, a higher observatory, to bring himself ever closer to the moon's embrace.'"

1033.m_mText: "'To erect this new tower, he not only spent vast fortunes but also poured every ounce of his ingenuity into its design. The tower soared to unprecedented heights.'"

1034.m_mText: "''It shall stand as the pinnacle of the continent!' he proclaimed to all, dismissing the very existence of mountains. The moment the tower's highest platform was barely habitable, he ascended with feverish anticipation.'"

1035.m_mText: "'But he never descended. A strike of lightning shook the castle, and when others ventured up, they found only a heap of ashes.'"

1036.m_mText: "'Curiously, the structure itself remained untouched, standing resolute for decades before it was finally dismantled.'"

1037.m_mText: "'That's rather perplexing,' Ressa mused. 'Wouldn't an architect of such renown have incorporated safeguards against such disasters?'"

2001001.m_mText: "'The investigation later showed it was just an oversight on his part. He didn't wait for nightfall but went up when the sky was covered with dark clouds, and he forgot to check if the workers had installed the lightning rods yet.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'So that's why you're afraid of thunder?' Ressa sensed there was more to the story."

2001003.m_mText: "'It's a story I've heard since childhood. I've always avoided high places on cloudy days,' Empousa said with a sigh."

2002001.m_mText: "'Some suspect it was murder. They believe the lightning rod was deliberately sabotaged. Plus, the new head of the family never saw eye to eye with the deceased.'"

2002002.m_mText: "'Well, if that's the case, you shouldn't have to fear thunder anymore,' Ressa reasoned."

2002003.m_mText: "'It's not something I can control. Whenever there's thunder, that story instantly comes to mind,' Empousa said, her body trembling slightly as if reliving the recent storm."

2003001.m_mText: "'Actually, someone in a nearby tower happened to see him standing atop the unfinished tower, holding what looked like a metal rod or sword.'"

2003002.m_mText: "'But why?!' Hati cried out. 'Was he trying to kill himself?'"

2003003.m_mText: "'Perhaps there are moments when people truly lose their grip on reality,' Ressa pondered before turning expectantly to Empousa for an answer."

2003004.m_mText: "'Everyone involved has long since turned to dust, along with the truth. For all we know, even that supposed witness was lying,' Empousa dismissed."

1.m_mText: "The Moonlight Sword of the Ganelon family embodies their ancestral legacy. It grows in strength as its wielder matures, and wanes as its master's life ebbs away."

1002.m_mText: "Perhaps it was the very absence of the sword that led the young woman to recognize her own uniqueness."

1003.m_mText: "Hati craned her neck to gaze at the towering watchtower. Atop it stood a vigilant clan member, eyes fixed intently on the distant lands of the Bathorys."

1004.m_mText: "A series of metallic clashes echoed behind Hati, punctuated by a distinct, ethereal resonance. One weapon clearly stood apart from the rest—Ganelon's Moonlight Sword."

1005.m_mText: "A young man's battle cry pierced the air and Hati spun around to witness the unfolding scene."

1006.m_mText: "Clive brandished his short sword and lunged at Gadric, who merely sidestepped the attack with surprising grace for such a rotund figure."

1007.m_mText: "'Watch your opponent's rhythm,' Gadric instructed calmly, his movements fluid as he deftly dodged and retreated."

1008.m_mText: "Clive, however, pressed on, his battle cries echoing with each wild swing of his short sword. The fire of youth had clearly ignited his temper."

1009.m_mText: "'Read your opponent's movements. Blind aggression only leaves you vulnerable,' Gadric advised patiently as he attempted to guide the young man back to the proper flow of battle."

1010.m_mText: "But Clive was deaf to any counsel. His mind was fixated on one goal: to land even just a hit."

1011.m_mText: "The duel had driven them to the edge of the sea. Clive nearly stumbled over the slippery rocks several times. As defeat loomed, the young warrior finally began to regain his composure."

1012.m_mText: "Gadric, in stark contrast, moved with perfect balance, as if he was still on solid ground. Hati surmised the duel was about to end any moment."

1013.m_mText: "Yet, as if by some inexplicable twist of fate, Gadric suddenly lost his footing. With a startled 'Ow,' he tumbled to the ground just inches from the water."

1014.m_mText: "'Uncle Gadric!' Hati cried out as she rushed to his aid. As she helped him up, disbelief coursed through her—surely his fall couldn't have been just due to carelessness."

1015.m_mText: "Clive, meanwhile, stood frozen in disbelief, his short sword dangling from his unattentive grasp."

1016.m_mText: "Gadric found himself sprawled upon the slippery rocks, absently scratching his equally smooth helmet."

1017.m_mText: "'Well, well,' he mused, 'it seems even the most seasoned warrior can falter. Fortunate this wasn't a real battle.' With Hati's aid, he sat up on the smooth rocks."

1018.m_mText: "'Looks like I need to hit the road, or I'll start rusting away,' Gadric said, catching Hati by surprise."

1019.m_mText: "Hati looked around for a fish or crab or other small critter—knowing Gadric, he probably lost his balance while trying to avoid stepping on one."

1020.m_mText: "'Uncle Gadric, did you really just fall by accident?' Clive finally asked the question that had been on both siblings' minds."

1021.m_mText: "'What?' Gadric looked at Clive, then at Hati, his face likely bewildered behind the helmet. 'Is there even such a thing as falling on purpose?'"

1022.m_mText: "'Like maybe you wanted to teach us some grand lesson about being aware of our surroundings during battle, or you fell to avoid stepping on small fish and shrimp, or maybe...'"

1023.m_mText: "'I think I just tripped over my own foot,' Gadric said, once again attempting to scratch his head through his helmet in embarrassment."

1024.m_mText: "Hati checked one last time to confirm there were no critters around before finally accepting Gadric's answer."

1025.m_mText: "'No way!' Clive exclaimed, still in disbelief. 'Uncle Gadric is the kingdom's First Knight!'"

1026.m_mText: "'The First Knight?' Uncle Gadric mused, looking up at the boy."

1027.m_mText: "'I haven't even crossed swords with every knight, how could I possibly claim to be the first among them? Even if I've won once, I might lose the second time.'"

1028.m_mText: "'But... but...' Clive stammered, his convictions visibly shaken."

1029.m_mText: "Gadric's words continued to chip away at the foundations of the young man's already fragile worldview."

1030.m_mText: "'There are many types of warriors in this world—those who fight on land, at sea, and from afar. This title of the kingdom's First Knight is nothing but empty words.'"

1031.m_mText: "Feeling for her brother, Hati sought to console him. 'I've heard the Roland family, the Horse, has raised many fierce knights, and the warriors of the Lion, the Griffiths, are no less powerful.'"

1032.m_mText: "'Don't forget your father,' Gadric added. 'The warriors of the Ganelon family are not only formidable, but also unwavering in their loyalty.'"

1033.m_mText: "Clive suddenly bristled with anger. With a dismissive 'Hmph,' he turned and strode towards the Fangtooth Tower. His father was just a stranger to him, and Clive couldn't care less about the man's strength."

1034.m_mText: "Clive Ganelon was fiercely loyal to both his family and the Church. However, it was this very devotion that rendered him an inadequate father."

1035.m_mText: "Gadric and Hati gingerly made their way from the seaside before quickening their pace to catch up with Clive. They were set to have lunch at the base of the tower."

1036.m_mText: "Hati unlocked the door at the base of the tower and retrieved a basket. Inside lay a hearty loaf of dark bread, a wedge of cheese, a cured ham, and a flask of wine."

1037.m_mText: "Clive lent a hand, slicing the bread, cheese, and ham to prepare their meal."

1038.m_mText: "Gadric settled himself on the stone steps and began to savor his lunch."

1039.m_mText: "Ever wonder how a garlic knight dines? Especially with garlic sauce on the menu."

1040.m_mText: "'Curious about the outcome of my last duel with your father?' Gadric asked suddenly, a slight smirk playing on his lips."

2001001.m_mText: "'It must have been you who won, right? Father said he couldn't beat you.'"

2001002.m_mText: "'When did he say that?' Gadric asked, gulping down the last of his wine and swallowing a mouthful of sandwich."

2001004.m_mText: "'I see.' Gadric lowered his head, took a bite of his sandwich, and chewed slowly, lost in his memories."

2002001.m_mText: "'Could it be that our father won?' Hati reasoned that since he mentioned it in front of them, the chances of her father winning must be quite high."

2002002.m_mText: "'He didn't tell you anything about it?' Gadric asked, his chewing coming to an abrupt halt."

2002003.m_mText: "Could there be more to this than just the contest? Hati's mind raced with speculation."

1.m_mText: "Do you grasp the true significance of those people's actions in the past? Just look around you now—their impact is evident in everything."

1002.m_mText: "Hati wasn't quite sure why she had returned to Fangtooth Tower. Perhaps it was to relive those cherished memories of practicing swordsmanship with her brother under Uncle Gadric's guidance."

1003.m_mText: "As she stood alone atop the tower, swinging a borrowed greatsword, it suddenly dawned on her—she simply didn't possess her brother's natural talent for swordsmanship."

1004.m_mText: "'What's this, dumb wolf?' Empousa's voice suddenly rang out from the stairway. 'Putting on a show at such dizzying heights with your abysmal swordsmanship?'"

1005.m_mText: "'None of your business, you damn bat!' Hati snapped, defiantly thrusting the sword into the floor."
